{"id":"kaibab-plateau-north-rim-parkway","generatedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"Arizona State Route 67","revisionId":1333632089,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaibab_Plateau-North_Rim_Parkway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaibab_Plateau-North_Rim_Parkway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Arizona State Route 67\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaibab_Plateau-North_Rim_Parkway","revisionId":1333632089,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Jacob Lake, AZ","to":"Grand Canyon NP, AZ","via":[]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Jacob Lake","state":"AZ","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":30.8,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Fredonia","Flagstaff"],"lat":36.71369,"lng":-112.21533,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Grand Canyon NP","state":"AZ","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":30.8,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["North entrance station","Bright Angel Point"],"lat":36.19874,"lng":-112.05274,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["SR 67 existed as a route to reach the north rim of the Grand Canyon National Park as early as 1927 as a dirt road. By 1935, the road had been improved to a gravel road, and by 1938 it had been paved. In 1941, the road was designated as a state highway and signed as SR 67. In 1985, the highway received the designation of Kaibab Plateau – North Rim Parkway as an Arizona State Scenic Byway. The designation included SR 67 in its entirety as well as extending south into Grand Canyon National Park. Two years later, ADOT obtained the right-of-way for improvement of the highway from its northern terminus approximately 10 miles (16 km) south. In 1989, an additional right-of-way was acquired by ADOT from its southern terminus approximately 5 miles (8.0 km) north. By June of that year, the parkway received the designation of a National Forest Scenic Byway, and in June 1998, the Kaibab Plateau – North Rim Parkway received another designation, this time as a National Scenic Byway. Since establishment, the route has not been realigned and retains its original routing."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Jacob Lake","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Jacob Lake","lat":36.71333333,"lng":-112.21638889,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Grand Canyon NP","d":"The drive ends here","q":"Grand Canyon NP","lat":36.0552608,"lng":-112.1218355,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Roadway Inventory Management Section, Multimodal Planning Division (December 31, 2013). \"2013 State Highway System Log\" (PDF). Arizona Department of Transportation. Retrieved October 17, 2019.","url":"https://azdot.gov/sites/default/files/2019/05/2013shslog.pdf"},{"n":2,"text":"Microsoft; Nokia. \"SR 67\" (Map). Bing Maps. Microsoft. Retrieved March 10, 2011.","url":"https://www.bing.com/maps/#"},{"n":3,"text":"\"Bright Angel Point Trail\". NPS.gov. Retrieved July 14, 2025.","url":"https://www.nps.gov/places/000/bright-angel-point-trail.htm"},{"n":4,"text":"Grand Canyon Area Map (PDF) (Map). National Park Service. Retrieved March 14, 2011.","url":"https://www.nps.gov/grca/planyourvisit/upload/GRCAmap2.pdf"},{"n":5,"text":"Clayton, Robin. \"Kaibab Plateau – North Rim National Scenic Byway\". Arizona Scenic Roads. Arizona Office of Tourism. Archived from the original on April 12, 2011. Retr